<div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">
                                
<p n="1">Prosperity! Fortune!</p>
                
<p n="1-2">Sixth year of Kampavarman.</p>
                
<p n="2-8">Mātavi, the wife 
<supplied reason="subaudible">of</supplied> Kāṭakati-y-araiyar, after renovating this glorious temple, having a front hall erected, renovating the monastery (pāḻi), 
<supplied reason="subaudible">and</supplied> having a glorious temple 
<supplied reason="subaudible">of</supplied> Yakṣa-Bhaṭṭāri erected, had  one big bell fed 
<supplied reason="explanation">
<foreign>ūṭṭuvittāḷ</foreign>,i.e. gave one big bell</supplied> to be given 
<supplied reason="explanation">
  <foreign>iṭṭa</foreign>
</supplied> to this 
<foreign>paḷḷi</foreign>.</p>
                
        </div>
        
         
<div type="translation" xml:lang="fra" resp="part:emfr">
                
         </div>

        
<div type="commentary">
                
<p n="5">The term 
<foreign>pāḻi</foreign> is polysemic. Several of its meanings, according to the MTL could apply here: temple, hermitage; cave, mountain cavern; sleeping place for human beings; small tank;flight of steps leading into a tank. IP: cavern. Sampath fn6: “Pali is a term, known in all the Jaina Literature, and means a ‘temple’ or sometimes ‘monastery’.”</p>
                
<p n="5">The term 
<foreign>paḷḷi</foreign> appears to be used here in the sense of the entire Jaina cultic place.</p>
        </div>

         
